T1  - AN INTEGRATIVE PROCESS MODEL OF COPING WITH JOB LOSS
AU  - Latack, Janina C.
AU  - Kinicki, Angelo J.
AU  - Prussia, Gregory E.
Y1  - 1995/04/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1995.9507312921
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1995.9507312921
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 311
EP  - 342
VL  - 20
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Although the stress of involuntary job loss is well documented, the process through which people cope and ultimately adapt following this stressful event needs clarification. This article provides a crucial next step by introducing new theory to explain how people cope with job loss. The process model developed in this article incorporates constructs from coping theory, control theory, and self-efficacy. Future research strategies are suggested regarding coping effectiveness and reciprocal causality.
AB  - Although the stress of involuntary job loss is well documented, the process through which people cope and ultimately adapt following this stressful event needs clarification. This article provides a crucial next step by introducing new theory to explain how people cope with job loss. The process model developed in this article incorporates constructs from coping theory, control theory, and self-efficacy. Future research strategies are suggested regarding coping effectiveness and reciprocal causality.
